🏗️ Create Table

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

💻 Example

```python id="create_table"
cursor.execute("""
CREATE TABLE employees (
    id INT AUTO_INCREMENT PRIMARY KEY,
    name VARCHAR(100),
    salary FLOAT
)
""")
```

---

📌 Table Structure

| Column | Type |
|----------|----------|
| id | INT |
| name | VARCHAR |
| salary | FLOAT |

---

➕ Insert Data

---

💻 Example

```python id="insert_data"
sql = """
INSERT INTO employees
(name, salary)
VALUES (%s, %s)
"""

values = (
    "Saakshi",
    50000
)

cursor.execute(
    sql,
    values
)

connection.commit()
```

---

⚠️ Why commit()?

```text id="commit_def"
commit() permanently saves changes to the database.
```

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

📥 Insert Multiple Records

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

💻 Example

```python id="insert_many"
sql = """
INSERT INTO employees
(name, salary)
VALUES (%s, %s)
"""

data = [

    ("Alex", 40000),

    ("Emma", 60000),

    ("John", 55000)

]

cursor.executemany(
    sql,
    data
)

connection.commit()
```

---

📖 Fetch Data

---

💻 Example

```python id="fetch_data"
cursor.execute(
    "SELECT * FROM employees"
)

records = cursor.fetchall()

for row in records:
    print(row)
```

---

▶️ Output

```text id="fetch_output"
(1, 'Saakshi', 50000)
(2, 'Alex', 40000)
```

---

📖 Fetch One Record

---

💻 Example

```python id="fetch_one"
